sher=State.gov |date=2017 |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Botswana ===\nPossession of child pornography is illegal in [[Botswana]] and punishable with between 5 and 15 years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186167.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Botswana |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Burkina Faso ===\nPossession of child pornography is illegal in [[Burkina Faso]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186170.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Burkina Faso |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Burundi ===\nPossession of child pornography is illegal in [[Burundi]] and punishable by fines and between 3 and 5 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186171.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Burundi |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Cameroon ===\nWhile there is no minimum age of consent in [[Cameroon]], the law prohibits the use of children for the production of pornography. Distributing child pornography or any document that \"could harm the dignity\" of a child is punishable by 5 to 10 years of imprisonment and fines from 5 million CFA francs to 10 million CFA francs. It is not known if possession of child pornography is illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186173.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Cameroon |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Comoros ===\nPossession and production of child pornography is illegal in [[Comoros]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186182.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Comoros |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Republic of the Congo ===\nChild pornography in the [[Republic of the Congo]] is punishable by up to 1 year in prison and a fine of up to 500,000 CFA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186185.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Republic of the Congo |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Central African Republic ===\nThe law in the [[Central African Republic]] does not prohibit child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186178.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Central African Republic |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Ivory Coast ===\nUsing children for pornographic films, pictures, or events is illegal in [[Ivory Coast]] and is punishable by between 1 month and 2 years of imprisonment and a fine of FCFA 30,000 to 300,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186187.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Cote d'Ivoire |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Djibouti ===\nUnder laws prohibiting attacks on \"good morals\", the sale, production, and distribution of '''all''' pornography, including child pornography, is illegal in [[Djibouti]] and punishable by 1 year in prison and a fine of up to DJF 200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186190.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Djibouti |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Equatorial Guinea ===\nThe law in [[Equatorial Guinea]] does not prohibit child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186191.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Equatorial Guinea |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Eritrea ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Eritrea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186194.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Gabon ===\nThe possession of '''all''' pornography, including child pornography, is illegal in [[Gabon]] and punishable by imprisonment from 6 months to one year and/or fines up to 222,000 CFA francs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186197.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== The Gambia ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[the Gambia]] and punishable by up to 5 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186199.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Ghana ===\nWhile the law in [[Ghana]] does not specifically prohibit child pornography, it can be prosecuted as an \"offense against public morals\" which is punishable by a maximum of 3 years in prison and/or a fine ranging from 120 to 600 cedis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186202.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Guinea ===\nChild pornography in [[Guinea]] is illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186203.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Guinea-Bissau ===\nThe law in [[Guinea-Bissau]] does not prohibit child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186206.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Lesotho ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Lesotho]] and is punishable by imprisonment of up to 2 years and 6 months and/or a fine up to 30,000 maloti. In child pornography production cases where a child is trafficked, the offender faces up to life imprisonment and a fine of 2 million maloti.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186209.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberia ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Liberia]] and is punishable by up to 5 years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186212.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Madagascar ===\nThe government in [[Madagascar]] in 2007 adopted a law modifying the criminal code to define child pornography, making it illegal. As of 2012, the laws have been used in court on several occasions but has not resulted in a conviction. Officials said the laws were often not uniformly interpreted or applied.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186213.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Mali ===\nChild pornography is considered a form of indecent assault under the criminal code in [[Mali]] and is punishable by 5 to 20 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186218.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Mauritania ===\nPossession of child pornography is illegal in [[Mauritania]] with penalties of 2 months to 1 year in prison and a 160,000 to 300,000 ouguiya fine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186219.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Mauritius ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186222.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Mozambique ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Mozambique]] but appears to be rarely prosecuted. In 2011, there were no reports of prosecutions for child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186224.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Namibia ===\nProduction and possession of child pornography is illegal in [[Namibia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186225.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Niger ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Niger]] and punishable by 3 to 5 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186227.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Nigeria ===\nThe Child Rights Act makes child pornography illegal in [[Nigeria]], but not all states have implemented it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186229.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Rwanda ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Rwanda]] and punishable by 5 to 10 years in prison and a fine of 200,000 to 500,000 Rwandan francs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186231.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe ===\nThe law in [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]] does not prohibit child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186234.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Senegal ===\n'''All''' pornography, including child pornography, is illegal in [[Senegal]], but it is uncertain if adult pornography is illegal, or if the simple possession of adult pornography is illegal.\n\n=== Sierra Leone ===\nWhile the Ministry of Social Welfare, Gender, and Children's Issues has indicated child pornography cases are covered under the Child Rights Act of 2007, which prohibits \"cruel, inhuman, and degrading treatment\" of children, the law in [[Sierra Leone]] does not prohibit child pornography. As of 2012, there is no record of anyone ever having been charged or convicted of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186239.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Somalia ===\nArticle 29 of [[Somalia]]'s [[Constitution of Somalia|national constitution]] defines a child as any individual under the age of 18, and stipulates that \"every child has the right to be protected from mistreatment, neglect, abuse, or degradation\".<ref name=\"Frspc\">{{cite web|title=The Federal Republic of Somalia \u2013 Provisional Constitution |url=http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |accessdate=13 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124010543/http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |archivedate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== South Africa ===\nChild pornography is illegal in South Africa and is punishable by fines and up to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186244.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== South Sudan ===\nThe law in [[South Sudan]] does not prohibit the possession of child pornography. The distribution of all pornography is illegal in South Sudan\n\n=== Sudan ===\nChild pornography is illegal in Sudan, but it is uncertain if it includes simple possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186245.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Togo ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Togo]] and is punishable by 5 to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186252.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Uganda ===\nAll pornography is illegal in Uganda, and the law does not distinguish between pornography and child pornography.\n\n=== Zambia ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Zambia]] with penalties of up to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186255.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Zimbabwe ===\nWhile it appears the law in [[Zimbabwe]] does not specifically prohibit child pornography, a person in possession of child pornography can be charged with public indecency which is punishable by a fine of $600, imprisonment up to 6 months, or both.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/af/186257.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n== Americas ==\n\n=== Argentina ===\nThe law in [[Argentina]] does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography, but child pornography possession with the intent to distribute is punishable by imprisonment ranging from 4 months to 2 years.\n\nAny person who produces, finances, offers, trades, publishes, facilitates, disseminates or distributes, by any means, any representation of a person under eighteen 18 years of age in explicit sexual activities or any representation of their genital parts for predominantly sexual purposes, as well the organization of live shows of explicit sexual representations involving such minors is punishable by imprisonment ranging from 6 months to 4 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://servicios.infoleg.gob.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/15000-19999/16546/texact.htm#17|title=CODIGO PENAL DE LA NACION ARGENTINA|website=servicios.infoleg.gob.ar}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2018 was promulgated a modification on the Penal Code, penalizing the possession of child pornography, with prison sentences between three and six years.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.infobae.com/politica/2018/04/23/el-gobierno-promulgo-la-ley-que-pena-la-tenencia-de-pornografia-infantil/ |title=El Gobierno promulg\u00f3 la ley que pena la tenencia de pornograf\u00eda infantil |date=23 April 2018 |work=[[Infobae]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Belize ===\nThe law in [[Belize]] does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> The distribution of all pornography is illegal.\n\n=== Brazil ===\nProduction, distribution and possession of child pornography are clearly illegal and widely prosecuted in [[Brazil]] in accordance with its Code of Minors. Also possibly illegal would be simple visualization and lack of denunciation, though it is not directly mentioned in the Code of Minors. Level of enforcement has historically varied by courts. Brazil also [[Ages of consent in South America#Brazil|criminalizes every kind of prostitution]] of those under 18 years of age more severely.\n\nWhile the simple visualization of [[Legal status of cartoon pornography depicting minors|cartoons depicting sexual acts involving apparently human minors]] may not be illegal in itself, possession and especially production and/or distribution can be interpreted in courts to be of the same level of actual child pornography, since legislation is vague on the subject (see Articles 241-C and 241-E of the Code of Minors). Such a scenario is very remote though, as Brazilian courts do not often charge people for [[victimless crime]]s, especially those related to sexual misconduct (for example, while the age of consent is 14, the 18-year-old sexual partner of a consenting 13-year-old was once freed after less than two days by a judge<ref>{{in lang|pt}} [http://estadao.br.msn.com/ultimas-noticias/artigo.aspx?cp-documentid=26333837 Brazilian justice system frees man, 18, arrested for publicly kissing young teenager, 13 \u2014 Last News \u2013 MSN Estad\u00e3o] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426000846/http://estadao.br.msn.com/ultimas-noticias/artigo.aspx?cp-documentid=26333837 |date=26 April 2012}}. Online version of [[O Estado de S. Paulo]] newspaper.</ref>).<!--\n\n\"Article 240. To produce, reproduce, direct, photograph, film or record, by any means, explicit sex scenes or pornography involving a child or adolescent (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nPenalty \u2013 imprisonment of 4 to 8 years and a fine. (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #1 Incurs the same penalties whom brokerages, facilitates, recruits, coerces, or otherwise mediates the participation of children and adolescents in the scenes mentioned in this article, or with those whom they contrascene. (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #2 The penalty is acrescented a further third if the agent commits the crime: (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nI \u2013 at the public position or function or at the pretext to excerce it; (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nII \u2013 prevailing itself of domestic relationships, co-habitation or hospitality; or (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nIII \u2013 prevailing itself of relations of affinity of consanguinity to the third degree, or by adoption, in position of guardian, custodian, mentor, employer of the victim or who, in any capacity, has authority over his/hers, be it with its consent. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nArticle 241. To sell or to expose to sell photograph, video or other record that contains explicit sexual or pornographic scenes involving children or adolescents: (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nPenalty \u2013 imprisonment of 4 to 8 years and a fine. (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nArticle 241-A. To offer, exchange, disponibilize, transmite, distribute, publish or divulge by any means, including through system of computing or telematics, photograph, video, or other record containing explicit sexual or pornographic scenes involving children or adolescents: (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nPenalty \u2013 imprisonment of 3 to 6 years and a fine. (Amended by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #1 The same penalties apply to those who: (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nI \u2013 ensures the facilities or services for the storage of photographs, footage or images treated in the caput of this Article; (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nII \u2013 secures, by any means, access to the internet for photographs, footage or images treated in the caput of this article. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #2 The conducts typified in sections I and II of section #1 of this Article shall be punishable when the legal representative for the service has been officially notified, fails to disable access to the illegal content treated in the caput of this article. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nArticle 241-B. Acquiring, possessing or storing by any means, photograph, video or other form of record that contains explicit sexual or pornographic scenes involving children or adolescents: (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nPenalty \u2013 imprisonment of 1 to 4 years and a fine. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #1 The penalty is reduced by {{frac|1|3}} to {{frac|2|3}} if the material referred to in the caput of this article is of small amount. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #2 There is no crime if the possession or storage is intended to communicate to the competent authorities the occurrence of the conduct described in Articles 240, 241, 241-A and 241-C of this Act, when the call is made by: (Included by law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nI \u2013 public officer in the exercise of its duties; (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nII \u2013 member of organization, legally constituted, which includes, among its institutional purposes, receiving, processing and forwarding news of the crimes listed in this paragraph; (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nIII \u2013 legal representative and officials of Internet Service Provider or service provided through computer network, upon receiving the news related materials made to the police, the prosecutor or the judiciary. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSECTION #3 The persons referred to in section #2 of this Article shall keep confidential the referred infringing material. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nArticle 241-C. To simulate the participation of children or adolescents in explicit sexual or pornographic scenes by tampering, digital editing or modification of photograph, video or any other form of visual representation: (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nPenalty \u2013 imprisonment of 1 to 3 years and a fine. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\nSingle paragraph. Incurs the same penalties whom sells, offers for sale, delivers, distributes, publishes or disseminates by any means, acquires, owns or holds the material produced in the form of the caput of this article. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\n\n(...)\n\nArticle 241-E. For the purpose of the crimes defined in this Law, the term \"explicit sexual or pornographic scenes\" means any situation involving children or adolescents in explicit sexual activities, '''real or simulated''' [''emphasis added''], or exhibition of the genitals of a child or adolescent for primarily sexual motivations. (Included by Law No. 11,829, 2008)\"--><ref>{{in lang|pt}} [http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/Leis/L8069Compilado.htm Code of Minors of Brazil] (Article 244-A)</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in Canada}}\nCanadian law forbids the production, distribution, and possession of child pornography. Possession of child pornography is punishable by up to 10 years in prison. Production and distribution of child pornography is punishable by up to 20 years in prison. Browsing for child pornography on the internet is punishable by up to 5 years in prison. Prohibitions cover visual representations of [[human sexual behavior|sexual activity]] by persons (real or imaginary) under the age of 18, depiction of their [[sexual organ]]/anal region for a sexual purpose, or any written material or visual representation that advocates child pornography offenses against a person under 18. There is an exception for material with [[art]]istic merit or an educational, scientific, or medical purpose. The law against simple possession of child pornography was declared void in [[British Columbia]] by a 1998 provincial court ruling but this decision was overturned two years later by the Supreme Court of Canada.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=R v Sharpe |date=13 January 1999 |court=Supreme Court of British Columbia |quote=As s-s.(4) is in violation of s.2(b) of the Charter and is not justified under s.1, s-s.(4) must be and is declared void. |url=http://www.cyber-rights.org/reports/rvsharpe.htm}}</ref> The high court further concluded that a \"person\" under the law could be either real or fictional and that the prohibition of written texts was potentially acceptable.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=R v Sharpe |date=26 January 2001 |court=Supreme Court of Canada |url=http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html |quote=The reach of the proscription is further broadened by extending it to the depiction of both real and imaginary persons.}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=R v Sharpe |date=26 January 2001 |court=Supreme Court of Canada |url=http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html |quote=...materials that advocate or counsel sexual offences with children may qualify}}</ref> Cases have now been prosecuted in Canada involving anime and manga child pornography.<ref name=\"animenewsnetwork.com\"/>\n\n=== Ecuador ===\nThe possession, storing, fabrication or distribution of child pornography or any other kind of sexually explicit pedophile material is illegal under Ecuadorian law.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.hoy.com.ec/noticias-ecuador/vacio-legal-para-delitos-en-internet-548346.html Vac\u00edo legal para delitos en internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104210821/http://www.hoy.com.ec/noticias-ecuador/vacio-legal-para-delitos-en-internet-548346.html |date=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Guyana ===\nThe law in [[Guyana]] does not specifically prohibit child pornography. However, the law does regulate the sale, publishing, or exhibiting of obscene material, defined as anything that could deprive or corrupt those open to immoral influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/wha/186520.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Jamaica ===\nThe production, possession, importation, exportation, and distribution of child pornography is illegal in [[Jamaica]] and is punishable by a maximum penalty of 23 years in prison and a fine of J$500,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/wha/186525.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n\nChild pornography is illegal in Mexico and laws are strictly enforced. Any person caught producing, distributing, possessing, owning, exporting, importing child pornography or browsing for child pornography over the internet, involving children engaging in sexually explicit conduct or posing in sexually explicit manners shall be punished with up to 12 years' imprisonment, with hard labor, as well as a fine up to [[Mexican peso|MXN $]]500,000. A second conviction for child pornography requires the offenders to be placed on the Sex Offender Registry permanently.\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in the United States}}\n[[File:Operation Protect Our Children banner.jpg|thumb|Warning Banner for [[Operation Protect Our Children]]]]\n\nAlthough child pornography may also be obscene, a legal term that refers to offensive or violent forms of pornography that have been declared by decisions by the U.S. Supreme Court to be outside the protection of the [[First Amendment of the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] regarding free speech,<ref name=NCJRS>{{cite web|title=Remarks of Arnold I Burns Before the Florida Law Enforcement Committee on Obscenity, Organized Crime and Child Pornography |url=http://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=109133 |publisher=National Institute of Justice |work=NCJ 109133 |date=3 December 1987}}</ref> it is defined differently from obscenity. [[Federal Sentencing Guidelines]] regarding child pornography differentiate between production, distribution and purchasing/receiving, and also include variations in severity based on the age of the child involved in the materials, with significant increases in penalties when the offense involves a prepubescent child or a child under the age of 12. The punishments are usually very severe normally ranging from 5 years' to 40 years' imprisonment. The U.S. laws against [[child pornography]] are always enforced and among the harshest in the world.<ref name=Sentencing9>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussc.gov/r_congress/SCAC.HTM |title=Sex Offenses Against Children: Findings and Recommendations Regarding Federal Penalties (as directed in the Sex Crimes Against Children Prevention Act of 1995, Section 6, Public Law 104-71) |publisher=United States Sentencing Commission |page=9 |date=June 1996 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090526083325/http://www.ussc.gov/r_congress/SCAC.HTM |archivedate=26 May 2009}}</ref> Despite the very harsh laws, the U.S. is one of the largest producers of child pornography in the world, behind Japan and Russia.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} The PROTECT Act of 2003 codifies much of the U.S. child pornography laws, including simulated child pornography, such as cartoons, and has been used to successfully prosecute individuals for possession of cartoon child pornography.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manga Collection Ruled \"Child Pornography\" By US Court |url=http://io9.com/5272107/manga-collection-ruled-child-pornography-by-us-court |accessdate=2015-07-03 |first=Annalee |last=Newitz |date=May 28, 2009 |newspaper=[[Gizmodo]]}}</ref> Fictional (simulated) child pornography, however, is legalized if and only if it passes the [[Miller test]].\n\n\n'''Uruguay'''\n\nUruguay does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/japan-outlaws-child-porn-possession|title=In this article about Japan says that some countries (including Uruguay) still didn't ban the possession of child pornography.|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref> But sale and distribution of child pornography is illegal and punished with 6 months to 12 years imprisonment.<ref>{{citation|title=Human trafficking in Uruguay|date=2019-09-22|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Human_trafficking_in_Uruguay&oldid=917133047|work=Wikipedia|language=en|accessdate=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n\n'''Venezuela'''\n\nVenezuela does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/japan-outlaws-child-porn-possession|title=In this article about Japan says that some countries (including Venezuela) still didn't ban the possession of child pornography.|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref> But sale and distribution of child pornography is illegal and punished by fines and/or imprisonment from 3 months to 4 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/4aba3eb6c.html|title=Refworld {{!}} 2008 Findings on the Worst Forms of Child Labor - Venezuela|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|accessdate=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== Asia ==\n\n=== Bangladesh ===\n\nThe possession, production, distribution and public sale of child pornography is illegal in [[Bangladesh]] and punishment by fines and up to 10 years' imprisonment. Children trafficking for \"illegal and immoral purposes\" is a capital offence in Bangladesh and the offenders can face up to life imprisonment or even the death penalty.\n\n=== China ===\nPornography of any kind, including child pornography is illegal in the People's Republic of China.<ref name=DeptStateCountryRepts>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186268.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}} \"Pornography of any kind is illegal, including child pornography. Under the criminal code, those producing, reproducing, publishing, selling, or disseminating obscene materials with the purpose of making a profit may be sentenced up to 3 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance, in addition to paying a fine. Offenders in serious cases may receive prison sentences of 3 to 10 years, in addition to paying a fine. If the case is especially serious, they are to be sentenced to 10 years or more in prison or given a life sentence, in addition to a fine or confiscation of property. Persons found disseminating obscene books, magazines, films, audio or video products, pictures, or other kinds of obscene materials, if the case is serious, may be sentenced up to 2 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance. Persons organizing the broadcast of obscene motion pictures or other audio or video products may be sentenced up to 3 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance, in addition to paying a fine. If the case is serious, they are to be sentenced to 3 years to 10 years in prison in addition to paying a fine.\" (US government public domain text)</ref> As of 2015 China has no specific law that refers to child pornography in particular.<ref name=ZhangLaney>Zhang, Laney (Foreign Law Specialist). \"[http://loc.gov/law/help/child-rights/china.php Children's Rights: China]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20090111215612/http://www.loc.gov/law/help/child-rights/china.php Archive]). [[Library of Congress]]. August 2007. Last updated 16 March 2015. Retrieved 25 April 2015. \"The PRC Criminal Law does not specifically regulate child pornography. Distributing pornography to minors under age 18 is punishable by a heavier penalty within the punishments for distributing pornography.\"</ref>\n\nUnder the criminal code of China, those producing, reproducing, publishing, selling, or disseminating obscene materials with the purpose of making a profit may be sentenced up to 3 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance, in addition to paying a fine. Offenders in serious cases may receive prison sentences of 3 to 10 years, in addition to paying a fine. If the case is especially serious, they are to be sentenced to 10 years or more in prison or given a life sentence, in addition to a fine or confiscation of property. Persons found disseminating obscene books, magazines, films, audio or video products, pictures, or other kinds of obscene materials, if the case is serious, may be sentenced up to 2 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance. Persons organizing the broadcast of obscene motion pictures or other audio or video products may be sentenced up to 3 years in prison or put under criminal detention or surveillance, in addition to paying a fine. If the case is serious, they are to be sentenced to 3 years to 10 years in prison in addition to paying a fine.<ref name=DeptStateCountryRepts/> Broadcasting or showing obscene materials to those under the age of 18 is also illegal and has more severe punishments compared to distribution to those 18 or older.\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\nAs in [[Mainland China]], child pornography of any kind is illegal in Hong Kong. The law makes it an offense to possess, produce, copy, import, or export pornography involving a child under 18 years of age, or to publish or cause to be published any advertisement that conveys or is likely to be understood as conveying the message that any person has published, publishes, or intends to publish any child pornography. The penalty for creation, publication, or advertisement of child pornography is 8 years' imprisonment, while possession carries a penalty of 5 years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/187483.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\nAll forms of [[pornographic material]] are illegal in India under [[Indian Penal code|IP Section-292, 293]]. Child pornography is Illegal by IT Act-67B.<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Government Act: Section 67 [B] in The Information Technology Act, 2000|url=https://indiankanoon.org/doc/176300164/|website=Indian Kanoon|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe laws of [[Government of India|India Government]] strictly prohibit child pornography. In February 2009, the [[Parliament of India]] successfully passed the ''Information Technology (Amendment) Bill'', which made creation of [[Information Technology Act, 2000|IT Act]] and transmission of child pornography illegal. The bill also enables India's law enforcement agencies to take action against those seeking child pornography. For example, browsing for child pornography on the internet can lead to 5 years in prison and [[Indian rupee|\u20b9]] 1 million fine.<ref>{{cite web |author=Swati Deshpande |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-16/india/28032470_1_cyber-terrorism-child-pornography-section-67b |title=Browsing child porn will land you in jail |publisher=The Times of India |date=16 February 2009 |accessdate=16 October 2009 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103075109/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-16/india/28032470_1_cyber-terrorism-child-pornography-section-67b |archive-date=3 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Iran ===\n'''All''' pornography, including child pornography, is illegal in [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/186637.pdf|title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Iran|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Indonesia ===\nIn Indonesia '''all''' pornography is forbidden but Indonesia has no laws regarding pornography online. Jakarta's Chinatown district is considered to be one of the largest pornographic bazaars in Southeast Asia. Indonesia has been called \"a heaven for child pornography\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/national/article/Lax-laws-making-Indonesia-Russia-child-porn-bases-1062285.php|title=Lax laws making Indonesia, Russia child-porn bases|work=seattlepi.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Japan ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in Japan}}\n\nThe law in [[Japan]] prohibits child pornography. The production, sale, distribution, commercialization, and/or possession of child pornography is illegal under Article 7 of the ''Act on Punishment of Activities Relating to Child Prostitution and Child Pornography, and the Protection of Children''<ref name=\"1999act\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japaneselawtranslation.go.jp/law/detail_main/?printID=&ky=work&re=02&page=18&vm=03&id=100 |title=Act on Punishment of Activities Relating to Child Prostitution and Child Pornography, and the Protection of Children |publisher=Japaneselawtranslation.go.jp |date=26 May 1999 |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> and is punishable by a maximum penalty of 5 years in prison and/or a fine of [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]5,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186276.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref> Possession of child pornography with any intent of distribution or sale is also illegal.<ref name=\"1999act\" /> New law regulations since 2014 require people in possession of child pornography to dispose of it within 1 year before they risk prosecution in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullen|first1=Jethro|title=Japan passes law banning possession of child pornography|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/17/world/asia/japan-child-porn-law/index.html|accessdate=13 March 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n=== Kazakhstan ===\nThe law in [[Kazakhstan]] does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In 2010, the government introduced a criminal statute on the production and distribution of child pornography. Those convicted face administrative penalties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/sca/186466.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Malaysia ===\nSection 4 to 10 of the Sexual Offenses Against Children Act 2017 criminalises the sale, production, distribution, and possession of child pornography, including sexually explicit material involving \"a person appearing to be a child.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Sexual Offenses Against Children Act 2017 |url=http://www.federalgazette.agc.gov.my/outputaktap/aktaBI_20170707_WJW008739BI.pdf |website=Malaysian Federal Government Gazette |accessdate=21 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe age of consent for sexual activity in Malaysia is 16 years and above for both males and females.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interpol.int/public/children/sexualabuse/nationallaws/csamalaysia.pdf|title=Internet / Home \u2013 INTERPOL|work=interpol.int|accessdate=15 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604025311/http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/csaMalaysia.pdf|archive-date=4 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Muslim non-governmental organization Pertubuhan Ikram Malaysia (Ikram) president Dr Mohd Parid Sheikh Ahmad pointed out - in the case of Mara scholar Nur Fitri Azmeer Nordin who was caught with 30,000 explicit images of naked children or children taking part in a sexual act that watching pornographic videos and images is also haram in Islam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Child pornography: It's never 'just porn'|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/child-pornography-its-never-just-porn|accessdate=13 March 2016|agency=Asia News Network|publisher=The Star|date=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== North Korea ===\n{{Further|Pornography in North Korea}}\nProducing, distributing, importing and watching all types of [[pornography]] is illegal in [[North Korea]].<ref name=\"HassigOh2015\">{{cite book |last1=Hassig |first1=Ralph |author2=Kongdan Oh |title=The Hidden People of North Korea: Everyday Life in the Hermit Kingdom |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7T19CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA106 |edition=2nd |date=2015 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |location=Lanham |isbn=978-1-4422-3719-3|page=106}}</ref> The country has ratified the [[Optional Protocol on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography]] of the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]],<ref>{{cite web |title=North Korea |author= |work=Human Rights Watch |date= |accessdate=21 September 2016 |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/north-korea |quote=}}</ref> but has enacted no legislation specific to [[child pornography]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.icmec.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Child-Pornography-Model-Law-8th-Ed-Final-linked.pdf#45 |page=34 |title=Child Pornography: Model Legislation & Global Review |edition=8th |date=2016 |publisher=International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children |accessdate=8 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218033714/http://www.icmec.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Child-Pornography-Model-Law-8th-Ed-Final-linked.pdf#45 |archive-date=18 December 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Pakistan===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Pakistan]]. The preparation, possession or distribution of any such data related to child pornography is illegal under the Pakistani law. Whoever commits an offence of child pornography shall be punished with imprisonment term not less than 14 years and may extend up to 20 years in prison with the fine of 1 million [[Pakistani rupees|Rupees]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1634144/1-na-approves-harsher-punishments-child-abuse/|title=NA approves harsher punishments for child abuse|accessdate=13 February 2018|publisher=Express tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/411340-Child-molester,-pornographer-to-face-up-to-20-years-imprisonment|title=Child molester, pornographer to face up to 20 years imprisonment|accessdate=25 October 2017|publisher=Dunya News}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\n{{Main|Child pornography in the Philippines}}\n\nThe Philippines passed Republic Act No. 9775 \"Anti Child Pornography Act\" in November 2009. The Act outlaws the production, creation, distribution and possession of child pornography. It also places obligations on mall operators and owners of commercial property to ensure that violations of child pornography are not being committed on their premises.\n\nControversially, the Act also creates obligations on internet-related service providers to ensure child pornography is not being stored or transmitted through their services. The Act requires internet service providers and internet hosting services to employ filtering software and to report child pornography violations within 7 days of discovery. How this obligation is to be implemented is yet to be seen. {{as of|February 2010}} the implementing rules and regulations were yet to be released by the National Telecommunications Commission and the Inter-Agency Council Against Child Pornography.\n\nThe law also expressly places obligations upon photo developers, information technology professionals, credit card companies, banks and anyone with direct knowledge of child pornography activities to report suspected child pornography materials and transaction within 7 days of discovery.\n\nPrior to the Anti-Child Pornography Act, it was already illegal to use children for pornography and to sell and distribute that material. Under section 9 of Republic Act No. 7610 \"Special Protection of Children Against Child Abuse, Exploitation and Discrimination Act\", its prohibited to hire, employ, use, persuade, induce or coerce a child into performing for obscene publications or pornographic materials.\n\nIn addition, the Anti-Trafficking in Persons Act (Republic Act no. 9208) also outlaws the [[trafficking of children]] for the use in pornographic material.\n\n=== Saudi Arabia ===\nAll pornography is illegal in Saudi Arabia, and the law makes no distinction between adult pornography and child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/nea/186447.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Singapore ===\nIt is illegal to keep, distribute or sell pornographic materials, under the [[Undesirable Publications Act 1967]], as well as section 292 of the Penal Code. It is also illegal to keep, distribute or sell pornographic films under sections 29 and 30 of the [[Films Act 1981]].<ref>{{cite web|title=What is the law on pornography in Singapore?|url=http://singaporelegaladvice.com/law-articles/what-is-the-law-on-pornography-in-singapore/|accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nICMEC Singapore may have built a voluntary Asia-Pacific Financial Coalition Against Child Pornography (APAC-FCACP) by bringing together representatives from the financial and technology industries along with members of the law enforcement community to fight online child sexual exploitation.<ref name=\"apac-fcacp\">{{cite web|title=Asia-Pacific Financial Coalition Against Child Pornography|url=http://www.icmec.org/apac-fcacp/|publisher=The International Centre for Missing and Exploited Children|accessdate=13 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313104713/http://www.icmec.org/apac-fcacp/|archive-date=13 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> This is modeled after the Financial Coalition Against Child Pornography in the United States.\n\n=== South Korea ===\nThe law in [[South Korea]] does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography, but production and distribution of child pornography is illegal and punishable by up to 1 year in prison or by fines which can total up to 20 million Korean Won; moreover, the criminal can be forced to wear an electronic ankle bracelet for up to 10 years, can be listed on the sex offenders registry for up to 20 years, and may be prohibited from working in child and youth related occupations.\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nProduction, distribution, sale and possession of child pornography is illegal in [[Sri Lanka]]. It is punishable by up to 20 years' imprisonment, severe fines and/or forfeiture of property.\n\n=== Syria ===\n'''All''' pornography, including child pornography is illegal in Syria, but is unclear if this includes simple possession of child pornography. The penalties for child pornography are also unknown and it is unclear if anyone was ever prosecuted for child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/nea/186449.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Taiwan ===\nChild and Adolescent Sex Exploitation Prevention Act criminalized the production, broadcast, distribution, exhibition of child pornography. Simple possession of such materials without justifiable cause is punishable by fines.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n=== Thailand ===\nThe production, distribution, import, or export of child pornography is illegal in [[Thailand]] and punishable by a maximum of 3 years in prison and a fine not more than 6,000 baht.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186310.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref> Child pornography possession has been illegal since December 8, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library2.parliament.go.th/giventake/content_nla2557/law86-080958-84.pdf|title=Criminal Code Amending Act (24th) B.E. 2558}}</ref>\n\n=== Vietnam ===\nThe production, distribution, dissemination, and sale of child pornography is illegal in [[Vietnam]] and is punishable by 3 to 10 years in prison. Simple possession of child pornography is most likely illegal as well, since the laws in Vietnam prohibit all pornography, regardless of circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186319.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n== Europe ==\n\n=== Albania ===\nAlbania does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crca.al/sites/default/files/publications/OPSC%20Alternative%20Report%20Albania%202012.pdf |title=ALBANIA ALTERNATIVE REPORT to the Optional Protocol of the Convention on the Rights of the Child on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography |last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> The production and distribution of child pornography is illegal in [[Albania]] and punishable by a fine of 1 million leks to 5 million leks and a prison sentence of 1 to 5 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186322.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Albania |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Andorra ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Andorra]] and punishable by up to 4 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186324.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Andorra |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> It is uncertain if simple possession of child pornography is illegal. \n\n=== Armenia ===\nChild pornography is illegal in [[Armenia]] and punishable by up to 7 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186326.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Armenia |publisher=State.gov |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Austria ===\nProduction and distribution of child pornography is punishable by up to 3 years in prison. Production with intent of distribution as well as import, export, and transportation are punishable by up to 5 years in prison. Possession of pornography with children under the age of 14 (\"''unm\u00fcndig''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ris.bka.gv.at/Dokumente/Bundesnormen/NOR40093644/NOR40093644.html |title=RIS Dokument |publisher=Ris.bka.gv.at |date=2009-08-31 |accessdate=2018-04-24}}</ref>) may result in a sentence up to 2 years, or up to 1 year if it contains pornographic material of children above the age of 14.\n\nAn exception to the prohibition of possession or production of pornographic content with children over the age of 14 exists if they consent and the material is only meant for personal use.\n \nPornographic depictions of fictional minors are generally legal, with the exception of photorealistic (literal translation: \"near to reality\") content, which is treated as regular child pornography.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Belarus ===\nThe law in [[Belarus]] does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itu.int/ITU-D/cyb/cybersecurity/cop/icmec-model-legislation-update-april-2010.pdf |title=International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> but production and distribution of pornographic materials depicting a minor is illegal and punishable by up to 13 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186331.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Belarus |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Belgium ===\nPossession, production and distribution of child pornography is illegal in [[Belgium]] and is enforced by authorities. Possessing child pornography can result to up to 1 year in prison, and producing or distributing child pornography is punishable by up to 15 years in prison. The law permits the prosecution of residents who commit such crimes while abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/253039.pdf |title=2015 Human Rights Reports: Belgium |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Croatia ===\nPossession, production and distribution of child pornography is illegal in [[Croatia]] and punishable by up to 5 years in prison.\n\nAlso, an adult intentionally exposing children to\npornography (including adult porn) may result in fines or a sentence of up to 1 year in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/186551.pdf |title=Croatia |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\nThe possession, manufacturing, and distribution of child pornography is illegal in the Czech Republic and punishable by up to 8 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186344.htm |title=2011 Human Rights Reports: Czech Republic |publisher=State.gov |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> Possession of child pornography was made illegal in 2007 and is punishable by up to 2 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.center.cz/business/pravo/zakony/trestni_zakon/cast2h5.aspx|title=Trestn\u00ed z\u00e1kon|work=center.cz}}</ref>\n\n=== Denmark ===\nPossession, distribution, and production of child pornography is illegal under Danish law, likewise is spectating such an act even without taking part. Specifically, \u00a7230, \u00a7235, and \u00a7235a in the Danish Penal Code are concerned with children and pornography, although the language is dated and vague. Maximum sentence for simple possession is 1 year in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/forms/r0710.aspx?id=142912#Kap24|title=Straffeloven \u2013 Bekendtg\u00f8relse af straffeloven \u2013 retsinformation.dk|work=retsinformation.dk}}</ref>\n\n=== Finland ===\nUnder Finnish law, it is illegal to possess, produce or distribute child pornography. Possession of child pornography is punishable by fine or imprisonment of 1 year while production or distribution of child pornography is punishable by fine or 2 years imprisonment.\n\n\"Aggravated\" distribution of child pornography depicting a child whom is (1) particularly young, (2) also subject to violence or particularly humiliating treatment, (3) the offence is committed in a particularly methodical manner or (4) the offence has been committed in the framework of a criminal organization; and is punishable by up to 6 years imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.finlex.fi/en/laki/kaannokset/1889/en18890039.pdf |title=Chapter 17, sections 18 and 19. |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!--{{Main article|Legal_status_of_cartoon_pornography_depicting_minors#Finland}}\nFantasy-based cartoon child pornography is legal in Finland.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}-->\n\n=== France ===\nChild pornography is illegal in France. The maximum penalty for its use and distribution is 5 years in prison and a [[Euro|\u20ac]]75,000 fine.<ref name=\"refFrance\">{{cite web |title=France: Children's Rights |work=Children's Rights: International Law and Practice |url=https://www.loc.gov/law/help/child-rights/pdfs/Children's%20Rights-France.pdf |publisher=Law Library of Congress |pages=71\u201385 |date=August 2007 |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\nChild pornography in [[Germany]] is illegal. German prosecution authorities and legal bodies of Germany's 16 states handle the definition of child pornography very differently. The German [[Sebastian Edathy|Edathy]] affair of 2013/2014 following the neglected cooperation of BKA within the Canadian child pornography uncoverings gave way for new legislation procedures in parliament to define the status of either posing or exhibitive pictures of minors. New laws were still in parliamentary debating as lately as 19 December 2014.\n\n=== Greece ===\nThe law in Greece prohibits the possession and circulation of child pornography, treating it as a felony and is punishable by 5 to 10 years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186357.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Hungary ===\nThe law in Hungary prohibits the possession of child pornography of any kind which is punishable by up to 3 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186359.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Iceland ===\nPossession of child pornography is illegal in [[Iceland]] and punishable by up to 2 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186361.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nThe Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998 prohibits the production, distribution, sale, publication and possession of child pornography. Penalties include prison sentences and fines. The most common way individuals in Ireland distribute or acquire child pornography is via the internet. Some ISPs have implemented filters that block sites containing child pornography. In early 2015, UPC set up an internet filtering system with the help of An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na (The Irish Police Service) to block child pornography which applies to all of its customers. If an internet user tries to access a blocked site, a message will be displayed stating that the material is illegal and that is why the site has been blocked. However, UPC does not pass on the details of customers who try to access blocked sites to An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na. However, not all ISPs have filters in place and filters can easily be bypassed using proxy servers.\n\n=== Italy ===\nProduction, possession, distribution of child pornography in all its forms is illegal in Italy. Italian law clearly designates child pornography as \"portraying or visually depicting any minor engaged or involved in sexually explicit activities, as well as the simple lascivous exhibition or genitals or of the pubic region\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altalex.com/index.php?idnot=49754|title=Pedopornografia solo in presenza di atteggiamenti esplicitamente sessuali|work=Altalex}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2 March 2006, prohibition also extends to [[simulated child pornography]] in a specific legal designation that defines virtual imagery as \"images realized through the modification of real photographs or images of minors, or parts thereof, with graphic elaboration techniques ... whose quality makes non-real situations appear as real\". This excludes drawings, cartoons, and other non-realistic simulated child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altalex.com/index.php?idnot=78|title=Norme contro la pedofilia e la pedopornografia anche a mezzo internet|work=Altalex}}</ref>\n\nProducers and distributors of child pornography are punished with imprisonment from 6 to 12 years, and with a fine ranging from 25.822 to 258.228 [[Euros]]. Possession of child pornography is punished with imprisonment up to 3 years, and with a minimum fine of \u20ac1500 (Codice penale, Article 600 ter, paragraph 5); sentences can be doubled or tripled if the quantity of child pornography found in possession of the culprit is \"vast\".\n\nSecondary punishment includes a lifetime ban from employment in schools and in public or private services, organizations, structures, institutions or business establishments mainly frequented by minors.\n\n=== Monaco ===\nProduction and possession of child pornography is illegal in [[Monaco]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Since April 2009, the government of Monaco uses a list established by the [[Internet Watch Foundation]] to block access to websites containing child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presse.gouv.mc/304/wwwnew.nsf/1909$/c10358afabbd2598c12575ae002896cfgb?OpenDocument&2Gb|title=Home > Press releases > Archives Humanitarian and Caritative > Fight against child pornography(Gb)|first=Robert|last=BOUHNIK|publisher=|accessdate=21 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112090613/http://www.presse.gouv.mc/304/wwwnew.nsf/1909$/c10358afabbd2598c12575ae002896cfgb?OpenDocument&2Gb|archive-date=12 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Netherlands ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in the Netherlands}}\n\nProduction, possession, and distribution of child pornography and accessing child pornography on the internet is illegal in the Netherlands and punishable by up to 8 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0001854/TweedeBoek/TitelXIV/Artikel240b/geldigheidsdatum_25-12-2012|title=wetten.nl \u2013 Wet- en regelgeving \u2013 Wetboek van Strafrecht \u2013 BWBR0001854|work=overheid.nl}}</ref>\n\n=== Portugal ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in Portugal}}\n\nChild pornography is statutorily criminalised in the Portuguese Criminal Code (C\u00f3digo Penal Portugu\u00eas). The age of sexual consent in Portugal is, in principle, 14 years of age. The participation of underage persons in pornographic scenes is subject to stricter standards however because they are subject to the general regime of adulthood, which was set by the Civil Code at the age of 18.\n\n=== Romania ===\nThe display, selling, dissemination, renting, distribution, and production of child pornography, defined as any pornographic material involving minors, is punishable by 1 to 5 years in prison. If these acts are done with the use of information technology, the punishment is 2 to 7 years. Unlawful accessing of child pornography through information technology is punished by 3 months to 3 years in prison or by a criminal fine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II/Q= |title=Penal Code of Romania, art. 376 |accessdate=5 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308121055/http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II%2FQ%3D |archive-date=8 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Russia ===\nRussia does not prohibit the simple possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecpat.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Child-Rights-Committee-report-on-the-Optional-Protocol-on-the-Sexual-Exploitation-of-Children-Russia.pdf |title=Sexual Exploitation of Children in the Russian Federation |last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> {{cn span|text=There was an attempt to prohibit it, but failed. But the production, sale and distribution trade turnover of child pornography materials, as well as involvement underage individuals into production of such materials is punishable by deprivation of liberty for a term of 2 to 15 years.|date=December 2019}}\n\n=== Slovakia ===\nThe production, distribution, or possession of child pornography is prohibited in [[Slovakia]]; the penalties for breaking the law range from 2 to 20 years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186403.htm |title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Spain ===\nThe law in Spain prohibits child pornography. The penal code criminalizes both using a minor \"to prepare any type of pornographic material\" and producing, selling, distributing, displaying, or facilitating the production, sale, dissemination, or exhibition, of \"any type\" of child pornography by \"any means\". Knowingly possessing child pornography is also penalized, carrying a potential prison sentence of up to 1 year. The penalty for the production, sale, or distribution of pornography in which a child under 18 years of age has been involved is imprisonment from 1 to 4 years or up to 8 years if the child is under 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186408.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|publisher=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nChild pornography is presumed to have been illegal prior to 1971. It was legal from 1971 to 1980, but now is illegal. The [[National Library of Sweden]] experienced a dispute regarding the alleged collection due to their legal obligation to archive all material printed on Swedish soil.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/17058/20090121 David Landes of Swedish \"The Local\": Swedish national library in child porn scandal] 21 January 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.kb.se/aktuellt/nyheter/2010/KBs-innehav-av-barnporr-kartlagt/ KB:s innehav av barnporr kartlagt] (Swedish)</ref> This became publicized as activist groups Hand in Hand and Anh\u00f6riga till sexuellt utnyttjade barn became involved.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/18704/20090406 Peter Vinthagen Simpson of Swedish \"The Local\": Swedish national library reported for child porn] 6 April 2009</ref>\n\"The criminalization of possession of the drawings would otherwise exceed what is necessary with regard to the purpose which has led to the restriction on freedom of expression and freedom of information.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20120615/41460|title=Manga images 'not child porn': Supreme Court|date=15 June 2012|website=www.thelocal.se}}</ref>\n\n===Switzerland===\nProduction of child pornography is illegal in Switzerland. In July 2014, the legal age for actors participating in pornography in Switzerland was raised from 16 to 18.\n\n===Turkey===\nThe production, import, duplication, transportation, storage, export, presenting the same to other's use, or possession of child pornography is illegal in [[Turkey]].\n\nArticle 226 of Turkish Penal Code (Law Nr. 5237) states that \"Any person who uses children in production of indecent scenes, words or articles shall be punished with imprisonment from 5 to 10 years and a daily fine up to 5,000 days. Any person who engages in importation, duplication, transportation, storage or export of these products, possession, or presents the same to other's use, shall be punished with imprisonment of 2 to 5 years and a daily fine up to 5,000 days.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=5237 S.l\u0131 T\u00fcrk Ceza Kanunu MADDE 226 - MADDE 226 \u015ferhleri |url=http://www.turkhukuksitesi.com/mevzuat.php?mid=5174 |website=www.turkhukuksitesi.com |accessdate=2016-02-20 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n=== Ukraine ===\nThe law in [[Ukraine]] does not prohibit simple possession of child pornography,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> but courts have the authority to limit access to websites which distribute child pornography and to impose financial penalties and prison sentences for those running the websites.\n\n[[Nina Karpachova]], the Ukrainian Parliament Commissioner for Human Rights, said in June 2011 that a significant amount of child pornography available on the internet originates in Ukraine. It is believed the child pornography market in Ukraine is worth about $100 million per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eur/186415.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in the United Kingdom}}\n\nIn the United Kingdom, it is illegal to take, make, distribute, show or possess an indecent image of a child under 18. Before 2003 it was illegal to take, make, distribute, show or possess an indecent image of a child under 16. The maximum sentence is 10 years' imprisonment for extreme cases, 5 years' imprisonment for high level cases, a summary conviction of 6 months' imprisonment and/or statutory maximum fine for lower level cases.\n\n== Oceania ==\n\n===Australia===\n{{Main|Child pornography laws in Australia}}\n\nActs such as possession, production and distribution of child pornography are illegal in [[Australia]] and can be punished by up to a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and/or a $275,000 fine.\nPeople have been successfully prosecuted after describing acts of abuse via MMS.<ref name=\"AFP\"/> [[Operation Auxin]] in September 2004 led to the arrest of almost 200 people on charges of child pornography, and \"sting\" operations are common.\n\nIn December 2008, a Sydney man was convicted with possessing child pornography after sexually explicit pictures of children characters from [[The Simpsons]] were found on his computer. The NSW Supreme Court upheld a Local Court decision that the animated Simpsons characters \"depicted\", and thus \"could be considered\", real people.<ref name=\"TheAge Dec2008\">{{cite news |title=Simpsons cartoon rip-off is child porn: judge |newspaper=The Age |date=8 December 2008 |url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/simpsons-cartoon-ripoff-is-child-porn-judge-20081208-6tmk.html| accessdate=18 November 2009 |quote=A NSW Supreme Court judge has ruled an internet cartoon in which lookalike child characters from The Simpsons engage in sexual acts is child pornography.}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2011, a Tasmanian man was convicted with possessing child pornography after police investigators discovered an electronic copy of [[The Pearl (magazine)|''The Pearl'']] by Anonymous on his computer. The Pearl is available for purchase within Australia and published by Harper Collins.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/child-porn-book-the-pearl-still-being-sold-in-australia-after-tasmanian-man-convicted-for-downloading-it/story-e6frg6ox-1226015197430 \"Tasmanian alderman David Traynor gets child porn conviction for book still sold in Australia\"]. ''The Australian''. 3 March 2011. Retrieved 7 April 2011</ref> The conviction was overturned on appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2011/08/11/252251_scalesofjustice.html|author=Matt Smith|title=Child porn finding revoked|work=The Mercury|date=11 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008050039/http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2011/08/11/252251_scalesofjustice.html|archivedate=8 October 2012|accessdate=11 August 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== New Zealand ===\nBrowsing for or attempting to privately gain access to child pornography is illegal in New Zealand and could possibly face up to 5 years in prison or a fine up to [[$NZ]]50,000. The production of child pornography as well as distribution carries stricter punishments. Distribution carries a penalty of up to 14 years in prison. Production of child pornography is considered a form of [[child sexual abuse]] under the criminal code of New Zealand which is punishable by up to 10 years' imprisonment or a fine up to [[$NZ]]200,000.\n\n=== Palau ===\nThe law in the [[Republic of Palau]] does not prohibit child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186297.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n=== Papua New Guinea ===\n'''All''' pornography, including child pornography, is illegal in [[Papua New Guinea]]. [[Pornography|Pornographic]] websites are blocked in the country. The possession, sale, import and export of pornography is punishable by up to 6 months' imprisonment with a fine up to 1,000,000 [[Papua New Guinean kina|kina]]. Child pornography is illegal in [[Papua New Guinea]] and punishable by 5 to 15 years' imprisonment and/or a fine up to 2 million kina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2011/eap/186299.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|work=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Legal status of cartoon pornography depicting minors]]\n*[[List of pornography laws by country]]\n*[[Debate regarding child pornography laws]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.ncmec.org/missingkids/servlet/PageServlet?LanguageCountry=en_US&PageId=2451 |author=National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (USA) |title=Child Pornography Fact Sheet |accessdate=22 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115225944/http://www.ncmec.org/missingkids/servlet/PageServlet?LanguageCountry=en_US&PageId=2451 |archive-date=15 November 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nspcc.org.uk/inform/research/reading_lists/child_abuse_images_and_the_internet_wda65568.html |author=National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children (UK) |title=Child abuse images and the internet: A reading list |accessdate=22 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203093949/http://www.nspcc.org.uk/inform/research/reading_lists/child_abuse_images_and_the_internet_wda65568.html |archive-date=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}\n\n{{Pedophilia}}\n{{Sexual ethics}}\n{{Sexual abuse}}\n{{Law country lists}}\n{{Pornography legality|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Child Pornography}}\n[[Category:Child pornography law]]\n[[Category:Age and society]]\n[[Category:Law-related lists]]\n[[Category:Minimum ages]]\n[[Category:Sexuality and age]]\n[[Category:Youth rights]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:Legality of child pornography by country.png|300px|right|thumb|A world map with sovereign states painted according to their legislation regarding child pornography.\n{{legend|#A349A4|Any kind of pornography (including child pornography) illegal.}}\n{{legend|#3F48CC|Any kind of child pornography (real or fictional) illegal.}}\n{{legend|#00A2E8|Real child pornography illegal.{{refn|name=Real|group=Note|These legislations generally allow fictional child pornography, but may still prohibit it under certain circumstances, such as when the material is judged too \"realistic\".}}}} \n{{legend|#B97A57|No laws against any kind of pornography, including real and fictional child pornography.}}\n{{legend|#BDC1C5|Data unavailable.}}]]\nThe '''legality of child pornography''' is explicitly addressed in 94 of the 187 [[Interpol]] member states as of 2008, according to research performed by the [[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]] (ICMEC) Koons Family Institute on International Law and Policy.<ref name=\"icmec\">{{cite web |url=http://www.missingkids.com/en_US/documents/CP_Legislation_Report.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120173350/http://www.missingkids.com/en_US/documents/CP_Legislation_Report.pdf |archivedate=20 November 2012 |title= Child Pornography: Model Legislation & Global Review|publisher=ICMEC |date=2008}}</ref><ref name=icmec2>{{cite web|url=http://www.icmec.org/en_X1/pdf/SummerNewsletter2006formatted.pdf |title=Child Pornography Not a Crime in Most Countries |year=2006 |accessdate=27 February 2010 |publisher=[[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]] |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602083205/http://www.icmec.org/en_X1/pdf/SummerNewsletter2006formatted.pdf |archivedate= 2 June 2010}}</ref> Of those 94 countries, 58 criminalized possession of [[child pornography]] regardless of intent to distribute.<ref name=\"icmec\"/> This figure does not count legislation outlawing all [[pornography]];<ref name=\"icmec\"/> figures that also include non-specific bans on all pornography would therefore be higher if available.\n\nChild pornography is illegal in most jurisdictions of the world. Convictions for possessing child pornography also usually include prison sentences, but those sentences are often converted to probation for first-time offenders.<ref name= Akdeniz11>{{cite book|title=Internet child pornography and the law: national and international responses |first=Yaman |last=Akdeniz| publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |year=2008|page=11|isbn=0-7546-2297-5}}</ref> Some nations such as Canada and Australia have laws banning cartoon, anime, manga or written child pornography and others require ISPs ([[Internet service providers]]) to monitor internet traffic to detect it.<ref name=AFP>{{cite news |url=http://www.afp.gov.au/media_releases/national/2007/queensland_man_charged_over_sms_child_pornography.html|title=Queensland man charged over SMS child pornography|date=17 July 2007|author=AFP|accessdate=22 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080729134713/http://www.afp.gov.au/media_releases/national/2007/queensland_man_charged_over_sms_child_pornography.html|archive-date=29 July 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref><ref name=\"animenewsnetwork.com\">[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2005-03-04/canadian-arrested-for-importing-loli-porn-manga Canadian Arrested for Importing Loli-porn Manga] (4 March 2005, [[Anime News Network]]). Retrieved 23 June 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra2009/ra_9775_2009.html |title=REPUBLIC ACT NO. 9775 |publisher=Lawphil.net |date= |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe United Nations Optional Protocol on the Rights of the Child requires states to outlaw the \"producing, distributing, disseminating, importing, exporting, offering, selling or possessing for the above purposes\" of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undemocracy.com/A-RES-54-263 |title=Article 3, (1)(c) |publisher=Undemocracy.com |date=25 May 2000 |accessdate=16 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120154810/http://www.undemocracy.com/A-RES-54-263 |archivedate=20 November 2012}}</ref> The Council of Europe's Cybercrime Convention, the [[Council of Europe Convention on the Protection of Children against Sexual Exploitation and Sexual Abuse]], and the EU Framework Decision that became active in 2006 require signatory or member states to criminalize all aspects of child pornography.<ref name= Akdeniz11/> Article 34 of the [[United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child]] (UNCRC) stated that all signatories shall take appropriate measures to prevent the exploitative use of children in pornographic performances and materials.\n\n== International treaties ==\n\nInternational obligations to pass specific laws against child pornography \"punishable by appropriate penalties that take into account their grave nature\" as well as enable extradition, mutual assistance in investigation, and seizure of property were mandated by the [[Optional Protocol on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography]].\n\nSome of the negotiations and reviews of the process took place at the [[World Congress against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children]] held in 1996 and 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csecworldcongress.org/en/index.htm |title=World Congress against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children |publisher=Csecworldcongress.org |date=27 July 2002 |accessdate=16 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316121435/http://www.csecworldcongress.org/en/index.htm |archivedate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Debate==\n\nWhile laws criminalizing [[child sexual abuse]] now exist in all countries of the world,<ref name=Levesque>{{cite book|title=Sexual Abuse of Children: A Human Rights Perspective |last= Levesque |first=Roger J. R. |publisher= Indiana University Press |year= 1999 |pages=1,5\u20136,176\u2013180|quote=The world community recently has recognized every child's fundamental human right to protection from sexual maltreatment. This right has been expressed in recent declarations, conventions, and programs of action. Indeed, the right to protection from sexual maltreatment is now entrenched so strongly in international human rights law that no country can relinquish its obligation.}}</ref><ref name=UNchildren>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ohchr.org/english/law/crc.htm |title=United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child |publisher=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights |year=1989 |quote=States Parties shall take all appropriate legislative, administrative, social and educational measures to protect the child from all forms of physical or mental violence, injury or abuse, neglect or negligent treatment, maltreatment or exploitation, including sexual abuse... States Parties undertake to protect the child from all forms of sexual exploitation and sexual abuse. For these purposes, States Parties shall in particular take all appropriate national, bilateral and multilateral measures to prevent: (a) The inducement or coercion of a child to engage in any unlawful sexual activity; (b) The exploitative use of children in prostitution or other unlawful sexual practices; (c) The exploitative use of children in pornographic performances and materials. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611182141/http://www2.ohchr.org/english/law/crc.htm |archivedate=2010-06-11}}</ref> more diversity of opinions exists on questions like exactly how young those depicted in [[pornography]] should be allowed to be, whether the mere possession of [[child pornography]] should be a crime, or whether sentences for such possession should be modified.\n\nIn 1999, in the case of ''[[R. v. Sharpe]]'', British Columbia's highest court struck down a law against possessing child pornography as unconstitutional.<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-23215648.html \"Canada Court Quashes Child-Porn Law\"]{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}, ''AP Online'', 1999-06-30</ref> That opinion, written by Justice Duncan Shaw, held, \"There is no evidence that demonstrates a significant increase in the danger to children caused by pornography\", and \"A person who is prone to act on his fantasies will likely do so irrespective of the availability of pornography.\"<ref>[http://www.efc.ca/pages/media/national-post.16jan99.html Top B.C. court strikes down child-porn law], The National Post, January 16, 1999</ref> The Opposition in the Canadian Parliament considered invoking the [[notwithstanding clause]] to override the court's ruling.<ref>[http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?collection=journals&handle=hein.journals/appeal6&div=7&id=&page= \"Judicial Activism in R. v. Sharpe: An Administration or Perversion of Justice?\"], ''Rev. Current L. & L. Reform'', 2000, pp. 14</ref> However, it was not necessary because the Canadian Supreme Court overturned the decision with several findings including that viewing such material makes it more likely that the viewer will abuse, that the existence of such materials further hurts the victims as they know of its existence, and that the demand for such images encourages the abuse.<ref>[http://scc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html ''R. v. Sharpe''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430210752/http://scc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html |date=April 30, 2008}} (26 January 2001). 1 S.C.R. 45, 2001 SCC 2. Retrieved February 20, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn the United States, some federal judges have argued that the U.S. Sentencing Guidelines' recommended penalties for possessors of child pornography are too harsh.<ref name=denverpost>[http://www.denverpost.com/ci_13887009 \"Federal judges argue for reduced sentences for child-porn convicts\"], ''The Denver Post'', November 29, 2009</ref> Judge [[Jack B. Weinstein]] of New York criticizes the mandatory sentence for possession of child pornography as often ''higher'' than the penalty for actually committing the act of child abuse it depicts. Furthermore, child pornography prosecutions have led to dozens of suicides, some of them among the innocently accused.<ref name=\"weinstein\">{{cite web|url=http://human-stupidity.com/stupid-dogma/teenage-sexuality/child-porn-laws-kill-destroy-lives-judge-jack-b-weinstein|title=Child porn laws kill, destroy lives(Judge Jack B. Weinstein)|date=1 November 2010|publisher=}}</ref> The requirement that people convicted of possessing child pornography pay restitution has been criticized by some judges and law professors. This has been particularly controversial in cases involving millions of dollars of restitution, as in those pertaining to the Misty Series.<ref>John Schwartz (February 2, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/us/03offender.html \"Child Pornography, and an Issue of Restitution\"], ''New York Times''</ref> But in 2010, the US Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that restitution directly to depicted minors was an appropriate penalty for possession of child pornography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20100901158|title=U.S. v. BAXTER - No. 09-30364. - 20100901158 - Leagle.com|website=Leagle}}</ref>\n\nDuring the nomination process at the 2008 Libertarian National Convention, [[anarcho-capitalist]] and U.S. Presidential candidate [[Mary Ruwart]] came under fire for her comment in her 1998 book, ''Short answers to the tough questions'', in which she stated her opposition not only to laws against possession of child pornography but even against its ''production'', based on her belief that such laws actually encourage such behavior by increasing prices.<ref>Nathan Thornburgh (May 21, 2008), [http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1808384,00.html \"Can the Libertarians Go Mainstream?\"], ''Time''</ref> Shane Cory, on behalf of the [[minarchism|minarchist]] United States Libertarian Party in his role as executive director, issued a response saying, \"We have an obligation to protect children from sexual exploitation and abuse, and we can do this by increasing communication between state and federal agencies to help combat this repulsive industry. While privacy rights should always be respected in the pursuit of child pornographers, more needs to be done to track down and prosecute the twisted individuals who exploit innocent children.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lp.org/media/article_578.shtml|title=Wayback Machine|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=20 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512053825/http://www.lp.org/media/article_578.shtml|archive-date=12 May 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Cory resigned after the party refused to vote on a resolution asking states to strongly enforce existing child porn laws.<ref>McCain, Robert Stacy (May 23, 2008), [http://spectator.org/archives/2008/05/23/fear-and-loathing-in-denver 0Fear and Loathing in Denver\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904033846/http://spectator.org/archives/2008/05/23/fear-and-loathing-in-denver |date=4 September 2009}}, ''The American Spectator''</ref>\n\n== Table ==\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove section|date=October 2019}}\n{{Original research|section|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:120px;\"| Country{{refn|name=RealSS|group=Note|May be either a [[sovereign]] state, a ''[[List of states with limited recognition|disputed state]]'', or a territory.}} !! Real child pornography !! Fictional child pornography !! Possession !! Sale !! Production !! Distribution !! Notes\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Abkhazia}} [[Abkhazia]] || Uncertain|| Uncertain || Uncertain || Uncertain || Uncertain || Uncertain || \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Albania}} [[Albania]] || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || Uncertain || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || All forms of child pornography are illegal.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Algeria}} [[Algeria]] || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || All forms of pornography are illegal.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Andorra}} [[Andorra]] || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || All forms of child pornography are illegal.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Argentina]] || {{no|Illegal}} || Uncertain || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} ||\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Armenia}} [[Armenia]] || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} ||\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Australia]] ''(including all territories)'' || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || {{no|Illegal}} || Child pornography is classed under extreme 